<Layout
  title="Statement of Purpose"
  description="Community-Based Mineral Stewardship: A Statement of Purpose by Nyonka Mining Cooperative Limited."
>
  <Section
    title="Community-Based Mineral Stewardship"
    subtitle="A Statement of Purpose"
  >
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl space-y-6 text-[#355E4A] leading-relaxed">
      <p class="font-semibold text-[#1F3D2B]">
        Nyonka Mining Cooperative Limited
      </p>

      <p>
        Nyonka Mining Cooperative Limited exists because in many rural parts of Zambia,
        mineral wealth has historically coexisted with poverty. For generations,
        communities have lived on mineral-bearing land without participation, ownership,
        or meaningful benefit, while value is extracted elsewhere or remains undeveloped.
        <strong>This contradiction is not accidental—it is structural.</strong>
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>The Cooperative was therefore organized as a corrective response.</strong>
      </p>

      <p>
        In recent years, the Government of the Republic of Zambia has consistently encouraged
        citizens to organize themselves into lawful, accountable structures—particularly
        cooperatives—so that local people may actively participate in the exploitation of
        natural resources, contribute to national development, and create employment and
        wealth within their own communities.
      </p>

      <p>
        Nyonka Mining Cooperative Limited aligns itself with this national direction and with
        the broader developmental vision articulated by
        <strong> His Excellency the President of the Republic of Zambia, Hakainde Hichilema</strong>,
        under which citizens are not passive beneficiaries of development, but active partners
        working hand in hand with Government to unlock economic potential.
      </p>

      <p>
        Our members are local people of Masaiti District, bound by shared land, shared history,
        and shared exclusion from the economic value of the resources beneath our feet. From
        as far back as living memory—including members born in the 1940s—the minerals in our
        area have not translated into employment, infrastructure, skills, or dignity for the
        people who live there.
      </p>

      <p>
        Where resources lie idle or inaccessible to communities, poverty becomes entrenched
        and opportunity migrates elsewhere.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Nyonka Mining Cooperative Limited was formed to break this cycle.</strong>
      </p>

      <p>
        We organized ourselves not out of convenience, but out of necessity. Individually,
        local people lack the legal standing, technical capacity, and institutional credibility
        required to engage the mining sector lawfully. Collectively, through a cooperative
        structure, we acquire discipline, accountability, and legitimacy.
      </p>

      <p>
        The cooperative model enables ordinary citizens to comply with the law, respect
        traditional authority, protect the environment, and participate meaningfully in the
        local and national economy.
      </p>

      <p>
        We recognize that mining, if left informal or uncoordinated, can be destructive. For
        this reason, we deliberately chose a regulated, transparent, and community-governed
        structure.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>
          Our ethos is rooted in lawfulness over informality, collective benefit over
          individual gain, and long-term development over short-term extraction.
        </strong>
      </p>

      <p>
        In this sense, Nyonka Mining Cooperative Limited represents a
        <strong> necessary intervention</strong>—not because mining must expand at all costs,
        but because exclusion, unemployment, and idle resources are themselves destabilizing
        forces.
      </p>

      <p>
        Where people are locked out of opportunity on their own land, informal and unsafe
        practices inevitably emerge. A cooperative offers a lawful alternative:
        <strong> order instead of chaos, accountability instead of exploitation, and shared
        prosperity instead of marginalization.</strong>
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>We do not claim perfection. We claim responsibility.</strong>
      </p>

      <p>
        Our operations are anchored in respect for traditional leadership, compliance with
        Zambian law, environmental stewardship, and fair participation of members and the
        wider community.
      </p>

      <p>
        The Cooperative exists to ensure that mineral development, where it occurs,
        <strong> happens with the people—not around them or in spite of them.</strong>
      </p>

      <p>
        Ultimately, the Cooperative’s work is intended to contribute beyond its immediate
        membership. By formalizing community participation in mining, Nyonka Mining Cooperative
        Limited seeks to generate <strong>direct employment</strong>, stimulate
        <strong> local value chains</strong>—including transport, supplies, services, and
        skills development—and ensure that mineral activity translates into
        <strong> tax-compliant production and national revenue.</strong>
      </p>

      <p>
        In doing so, the Cooperative positions itself as a practical partner in Zambia’s
        broader economic objectives: converting natural resources into lawful enterprise,
        productive work, and shared prosperity that benefits communities, districts, and the
        nation as a whole.
      </p>

      <p>
        In this context, Nyonka Mining Cooperative Limited is not merely an enterprise.
        <strong> It is a social instrument</strong>—formed to convert dormant mineral potential
        into structured employment, skills development, and community upliftment.
      </p>

      <p>
        Where history has produced imbalance, the cooperative exists to restore balance.
      </p>

      <p class="font-semibold text-[#1F3D2B]">
        That is our ethos.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Section>
</Layout>
